COVID Excess Death

Viguen Poghosyan, Davit Sargsyan

Date: Sat Apr 22 12:41:53 2023

Meeting 10/28/22 Javier: 1. use decompose function (Fourier transform) 2. find top 3 frequencies (for 12-month frequency) 3. remove 12-months signal 4. run decompose again for longer frequency (24 or 36 month?)
2. Repeat seasonality analysis for each of the 20 states and for each cause of death.
3. How to make this analysis for all 20 states in a single model (similar to random effects model idea)?
4. Use new data from Nuria (US-wide, not separated by states).
5. F-Test residuals from the 12month and 13 month (seasonality of residuals). Other ways to compare? bootstrap?
6. Try to get daily temperatures. What part of months are the peaks - beginning, middle or end? are the peaks between 2 months?
7. Using lockdown, mask and vaccination data, model residuals of the forecast (COVID years). Might be lag. Talk to Yajie.
8. Weighted PCA? Talk to Yajie.
9. For PCA, transform log(1+ a%) - log(1 - b%). Use DMR::trans2 function.

3.5 Modeling

for (i in 1:nlevels(dt2$Cause)) {
  # Subset data
  cod <- levels(dt2$Cause)[i]
  
  tmp <- droplevels(dt2[Cause == cod,])
  
  tmp$dt <- as.numeric(tmp$Date)
  tmp$dt_sqr <- tmp$dt^2
  
  # LM
  m1 <- lm(Rate ~ (dt + dt_sqr)*State,
           data = tmp[set == "trn"])
  
  tmp$prd1 <- predict(m1,
                      newdata = tmp)
  
  # Plot
  p1 <- ggplot(tmp,
               aes(x = Date,
                   y = Rate,
                   group = Cause)) +
    facet_wrap(~ State) +
    geom_ribbon(aes(xmin = min(tmp$Date[tmp$set == "tst"]),
                    xmax = max(tmp$Date[tmp$set == "tst"]),
                    ymin = -Inf,
                    ymax = Inf),
                orientation = "y",
                fill = "green",
                alpha = 0.3) +
    geom_line(color = "gray") +
    geom_line(aes(x = Date,
                  y = prd1),
              color = "red") +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq.Date(from = min(dt2$Date),
                                         to = max(dt2$Date),
                                         by = 365.25)) +
    ggtitle(cod) +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(legend.position = "none",
          axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90,
                                     hjust = 1))
  
  m3 <- try({
    # NLME
    m3 <- nlme(Rate ~ b0 + b1*dt + b2*dt^2 + b3*sin(b4 + b5*dt),
               data = tmp[set == "trn"],
               random = b0 + b1 + b2 + b3 + b4 + b5 ~ 1 | State,
               fixed = b0 + b1 + b2 + b3 + b4 + b5 ~ 1,
               start = list(fixed = c(b0 = m1$coefficients[1], # linear intercept
                                      b1 = m1$coefficients[2], # linear slope
                                      b2 = m1$coefficients[3], # square term, i.e. non-linearity of the trend
                                      b3 = 10000, # wave magnitude
                                      b4 = 1, # sin shift to the left
                                      b5 = 0.018)),# wave length(> 1 shortens, < 1 elongates)
               control = nlmeControl(maxIter = 500)) 
  })
  if(class(m3)[1] != "try-error") {
    
    tmp$prd3 <- predict(m3,
                        newdata = tmp)
    
    dtt[[i]] <- tmp
    
    # Save coefficients
    betas[[i]] <- m3$coefficients$fixed
    
    # Save Mean Absolute Percent Error (MAPE)
    ## All states
    mape[[i]] <- tmp[, .(mape = 100*mean(abs(Rate - prd3)/(Rate))),
                     by = set]
    
    ## By State
    mape_state[[i]] <- tmp[, .(mape = 100*mean(abs(Rate - prd3)/(Rate))),
                           by = list(State,
                                     set)]
    # Add predicted curve
    p1 <- p1 +
      geom_line(data = tmp,
                aes(x = Date,
                    y = prd3),
                color = "blue")
  }
  
  # Save plot
  tiff(filename = paste0("tmp/",
                         cod,
                         ".tiff"),
       height = 10,
       width = 10,
       units = 'in',
       res = 300,
       compression = "lzw+p")
  print(p1)
  graphics.off()
}

5.4 Spectral density of a time serie

Fourier transform decomposes functions into frequency components. Highest peak represents the largest frequency. In this case, 1/12, i.e., 12-month repeated periods.

xx <- spectrum(diab_ca$Rate[diab_ca$set == "trn"])

# The highest peak is around the 12-months cycle
abline(v = 1/12, 
       col = 2, # red
       lty = 2,
       lw = 2)

# Other top peaks
abline(v = 1/60,
       col = 3, # blue
       lty = 2)
abline(v = 1/6, 
       col = 4, # green
       lty = 2)


tmp <- data.table(x = 1/xx$freq,
                  y = xx$spec)
ggplot(tmp[x < 25],
       aes(x = x,
           y = y)) +
  geom_line() +
